flowchart LR

  subgraph WHY["1. Why this group exists"]
    W1["The platform cannot stop at admitted traffic"]
    W2["It has to turn admitted live traffic into meaningful, explainable, bounded real-time decision truth"]
    W3["The RTDL framing makes that the core plane question: can this network turn admitted live traffic into meaningful, explainable, auditable, stable real-time decisions under production load?"]
    W4["The plane is explicitly composed of the boundaries we interrogated: CSFB, IEG, OFP, DL, DF, and AL"]
  end

  subgraph PATHS["2. Why the six paths are justified together"]
    P1["Entity and relationship projection"]
    P2["Joined context formation"]
    P3["Online feature readiness"]
    P4["Decision guardrail"]
    P5["Decision formation"]
    P6["Action and outcome emission"]
    P7["Projection proves the platform builds current graph truth rather than assuming it from schema or payloads"]
    P8["Joined context proves thin traffic becomes explicit time-safe runtime context inside the platform rather than arriving pre-fattened"]
    P9["Online feature readiness proves context is not yet enough; feature truth is its own boundary with readiness and freshness semantics"]
    P10["Decision guardrail proves the system separates inputs exist from it is safe to proceed, and treats degrade posture as a first-class runtime truth"]
    P11["Decision formation proves decisions are explicit provenance-carrying outputs rather than being implied later by actions"]
    P12["Action and outcome emission proves decisions become deterministic platform effects under their own owned boundary rather than dissolving into downstream side effects"]
    P13["Taken together, the six paths prove Group 3 is a chained runtime truth system rather than the scoring part in some vague sense"]
  end

  subgraph CLAIM["3. Group-level claim"]
    G1["The platform turns admitted traffic into governed real-time decision truth through a bounded sequence of owned runtime boundaries"]
    G2["The current wired system is intentionally constructing projection truth, context truth, feature truth, guardrail truth, decision truth, and action or outcome truth"]
    G3["That makes the system look like a genuine decision architecture rather than events merely moving through services"]
  end

  subgraph PROOF["4. What this group proves for A"]
    A1["Strongest closure: continuity, existence, and safety"]
    A2["Continuity closes because the runtime path from admitted traffic to emitted action is explicitly staged: traffic/context handoff, projection, joined context, feature readiness, guardrail posture, decision, and action/outcome"]
    A3["The run-process reinforces that structure by separating RTDL catch-up closure from decision-chain closure rather than pretending RTDL alive automatically means decisioning is closed"]
    A4["Existence closes because these boundaries are materially seated in the current wired RTDL plane: bounded live-runtime oracle scope, concrete worker/state/downstream handoff surfaces, distinct decision-side and projection/context components, and named downstream bus surfaces"]
    A5["Safety closes because the whole group is governed by real semantic boundaries: no future leakage into runtime, no truth-product leakage into live decisioning, no false-ready from partial or mis-scoped context, no false fail-closed from stale health artifacts, and no silent confusion between advisory degradation and real insufficiency"]
    A6["It also gives meaningful uniqueness closure: one active runtime route per phase or run, one bounded live-runtime oracle output set, and explicit truth ownership between context, feature, guardrail, decision, and action boundaries"]
  end

  subgraph AMBIG["5. A ambiguities to carry upward"]
    M1["The biggest A ambiguity is not whether the plane exists; it clearly does"]
    M2["The ambiguity is how to explain the seating cleanly without making it sound messier than it is"]
    M3["There are different runtime realizations and retained runtime postures across the RTDL plane"]
    M4["That should be explained as one coherent RTDL plane with different owned runtime boundaries rather than as an untidy mixed stack"]
    M5["The copied baseline wired view should stay the primary reader-facing object for A, while broader managed-stream posture remains supporting context"]
    M6["The second ambiguity is cross-plane: active bundle and policy authority is consumed inside Group 3 but actually owned upstream by the learning and registry group"]
    M7["So in A we need to keep saying Group 3 consumes runtime authority correctly; it does not own active-bundle truth"]
  end

  subgraph PARK["6. Bi spillover to park"]
    B1["Questions about RTDL lag, checkpoint age, latency, feature freshness, restart-to-green, false fail-closed rate under realistic faults, and decision/action tails under target throughput belong later in Bi"]
    B2["For A, Group 3 only needs to prove that the current wired platform has a real, bounded, intentional runtime decision graph with explicit truth boundaries and concrete seating"]
  end

  subgraph VERDICT["7. Group verdict"]
    V1["Group 3 proves that the platform does not merely score events; it constructs real-time decision truth through a bounded chain of owned runtime boundaries"]
    V2["This is a major A win because the current wired system has a genuine decision architecture: not just inputs and outputs, but explicit internal truths for projection, context, feature readiness, safety posture, decision formation, and action emission"]
  end

